25|$|Like the M-130, the M-156/PS-30 was a four-engined, high-wing {{design with}} the wing mounted atop a pylon {{extension}} of the fuselage (hull). While the M-156/PS-30 retained the same length as its predecessor, its wingspan was {{increased by more than}} 27ft (8.2m) with the addition of flaps for increased control. The M-156/PS-30 also differed from the M-130 by having a <b>horizontal</b> <b>stabilizer</b> mounted atop a pylon {{at the rear of the}} hull, with twin vertical stabilizers and twin rudders located atop the <b>horizontal</b> <b>stabilizer.</b>|$|E
25|$|Boeing Aircraft Company {{operates}} a manufacturing plant {{at the airport}} which manufactures vertical <b>stabilizers</b> and <b>horizontal</b> <b>stabilizers</b> for the Boeing 787 as well as components for the Boeing 737.|$|R
50|$|The term {{can also}} be applied to {{horizontal}} surfaces in general (such as canards or <b>horizontal</b> <b>stabilizers)</b> for the angle they make relative the longitudinal axis of the fuselage.|$|R
